title: Modify notebook to download from S3 instead of build from source
body:
Added this section so users don't need to build the extension from source:

```python
import platform

def extension_uri():
    version = '0.0.1'
    uname = platform.uname()
    arch = uname.machine  # arm64, x86_64
    system = uname.system.lower()
    system = {'darwin': 'macosx'}.get(system, system)
    uri_root = 'https://eto-public.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/repo/lance_duckdb'
    uri = f'{uri_root}/{version}/lance.duckdb_extension.{system}.{arch}.zip'
    return uri


!curl {extension_uri()} --output lance.duckdb_extension.zip
!unzip -o lance.duckdb_extension.zip
!rm lance.duckdb_extension.zip
```

I uploaded arm and linux zips:

title: Pandas extension dtype for image
body:
We have the Image arrow extension type but it breaks to_pandas conversion.
Here we implement a pandas extension dtype for ImageArray with ImageUri's.
It is backed by a string ndarray. 

Note that this requires copying the strings
which impacts performance a lot. A later optimization could be to directly
back this with arrow array.

References:

https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/development/extending.html#extension-types

https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/development/extending.html#testing-extension-arrays

title: Create pandas extension dtypes for Image, Box2d, and Label
body:
Currently we can't convert to/from Lance extension types to pandas because they don't have an implicit conversion. Instead if we define the proper pandas extension dtype (https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.api.extensions.ExtensionDtype.html and https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.api.extensions.ExtensionArray.html), it makes it a lot easier to convert data into Lance format. 

e.g., we want to be able to do something like:

```python
df["image"] = df.image.astype("image")
pa.Table.from_pandas(df)
```

title: Create a masonry layout image grid visualization in jupyter notebook
body:
Currently a single Lance Image knows how to show itself in Jupyter notebooks. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/759245/193160659-1aa96584-b3f9-45b9-b0c0-180d9556ac53.png)


However, there isn't a good way to show an image grid automatically.

Desired behavior: if you evaluate an ImageArray instance in Jupyter, it shows the first 10 and last 10 images (configurable) in a grid

Context:

Seaborn and Matplotlib have image grids you can use to plot and grid: https://seaborn-image.sarthakjariwala.com/en/latest/api/ImageGrid.html, https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/axes_grid1/simple_axesgrid.html, but it assumes all of the images are the same dimensions. Instead, it would be great to use a masonry layout: https://webdesign.tutsplus.com/tutorials/masonry-layouts-with-css-grid-and-object-fit-cover--cms-37989
